  "prompt": "I'm presenting some mobile app designs for a portfolio presentation in an interview. Should I make the designs be the full height of the PowerPoint, or do I need to make room for a title of the screen?",
  "response": "It's a good question and the answer depends on a few factors, but generally, **you should include a title or short description *and* not make the designs full height.** Here's a breakdown of the reasoning and best practices:\n\n**Why Not Full Height?**\n\n*   **Context and Hierarchy:** Your designs don't exist in a vacuum. You need to provide context. A title or short description immediately tells the interviewer:\n    *   *What screen they're looking at:* e.g., \"Login Screen,\" \"Product Detail Page,\" \"Onboarding - Step 2.\"\n    *   *The primary purpose of the screen:* e.g., \"User authentication,\" \"Displaying product information,\" \"Guiding new users.\"\n    *   This avoids confusion and helps them quickly understand the intent of your design.\n*   **Legibility and Focus:** If the design goes all the way to the edge of the slide, it can feel cramped and overwhelming. Giving it some breathing room makes it easier to focus on the design itself.\n*   **Presentation Aesthetics:** Full-height designs can look less polished and considered. Leaving a dedicated space for a title demonstrates intention and attention to detail in your presentation design.\n*   **Space for Annotations (Optional):** If you want to briefly call out specific elements or features of the design, having a bit of extra space above/below can be beneficial.\n\n**What to Include (Title/Description):**\n\n*   **Screen Title:** A concise name that identifies the screen (e.g., \"Dashboard,\" \"Settings,\" \"Checkout\").\n*   **Short Description (Optional but Recommended):** One or two sentences explaining the screen's primary function or goal. For example:\n    *   \"Dashboard: Provides users with a high-level overview of their account activity.\"\n    *   \"Checkout: Guides users through the payment and shipping process.\"\n*   **Design Rationale (If Relevant):** If there's a specific design decision you want to highlight immediately, you could include a short phrase about it (e.g., \"Simplified navigation for improved usability\").\n\n**Recommended Layout:**\n\n1.  **Title/Description Area (Top):**  Leave space at the top of the slide for your title and description.  This could be a consistent header area for all slides.\n\n2.  **Design Display (Center):** Place your mobile app design in the center of the slide, leaving margins on all sides.  Make sure it's large enough to be easily visible, but not so large that it feels overwhelming. Aim for good visual balance.\n\n3.  **Optional Callouts/Annotations:** If you want to highlight specific features, use callouts (arrows, circles) and brief text labels to point them out.\n\n**Example:**\n\n```\n[Top of Slide: Title Area]\n**Screen Title:**  Product Detail Page\n**Description:** Displays comprehensive product information, customer reviews, and purchase options.\n\n[Center of Slide:  Mobile App Design Image]\n\n[Optional: Small callout pointing to a key feature, like the \"Add to Cart\" button, with a short label: \"Prominent Add to Cart button for easy purchasing\"]\n```\n\n**Key Considerations for Your Interview:**\n\n*   **Consistency:** Maintain a consistent slide layout throughout your presentation.  This makes it easier for the interviewer to follow along.\n*   **Readability:** Ensure your titles and descriptions are large enough to be easily read, even from a distance. Use clear and concise language.\n*   **Visual Hierarchy:** Make the title and description visually distinct from the app design itself.  Use different font sizes, colors, or background treatments to create a clear visual hierarchy.\n*   **Focus on the Design:** While context is important, the app design should still be the focal point of the slide.  Avoid cluttering the slide with too much text or unnecessary graphics.\n*   **Practice:** Rehearse your presentation to ensure you can smoothly transition between slides and explain the design rationale behind each screen.\n\n**In summary: Don't go full height. Make room for a clear title and a brief description to provide context and enhance the overall presentation quality.**  Good luck with your interview!\n",
